title: C-12(X,XN)C-11 and Al-27(X,X2PN)Na-24 Cross Sections At High Energies

x4freetext: C-12(X,XN)C-11 and Al-27(X,X2PN)Na-24 Cross Sections
At High Energies

x4codes.hlp: Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, Berkeley, CA, United States of America
Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, Berkeley, CA, United States of America

x4freetext: One Purpose of this Work was to Demonstrate the Effect
Of Energy Degraders Placed Close to the Targets and
Resulting in Apparently Higher Cross Sections Due to
Secondary Charged Particles Emerging from the Degrader.
A Correction Factor was Determined For the Different
Projectiles and Absorbers Used and Applied to All Data
Measured with Absorbers in Front of the Target. Such
Measurements, Referred to As `Poor Geometry`, are
Marked with a Flag. All Other (UNFLAGGED) Data were
Measured Without Absorbers or with the Absorber Placed
Far Off the Target, Both Separated by a Steering Magnet
And a Collimating System (`GOOD GEOMETRY`).
1. The Following Errors were Specified-
Self-Absorption (+-3%), Condenser and Electrometer
Calibration (LESS THAN +-1%), Counter Efficiency (+1%),
Foil Thickness, Determined by Weighing (ABOUT 0.1%),
Secondary Particle Effect (+-2%), Knock-On Electrons
Influencing the Beam Current Measurement (+-1 TO +-4%),
Beam Spatial Distribution (+1.25%), Neutron
Contamination (-1.25%), Half-Life Uncertainty (LESS
THAN +-1%). The Accuracy of the Measurements is
Estimated to be +5 and -4 % For 350 MeV Protons
And 190 MeV Deuterons.
Error Values Given in the Data Tables are Standard
Errors of a Single Measurement, Which
Do not Include Estimated Uncertainties Due to
Possible Systematic Effects.
The Beams Used were Monoenergetic to Within 1%.
Corrections For Self-Absorption in the Activated Foils,
Detector Efficiencies and Secondary Electrons Affecting
The Faraday Cup Readings were Empirically Determined.
The Influence of a 1.25 % Portion of the Beam
Collected in the Faraday Cup But Missing the Target
Foils was Almost Precisely Compensated by Reactions
Induced by Secondary Neutrons. Both Effects were not
Corrected For. Correction Factors For All Data Measured
In `Poor Geometry` were Also Applied.
Lakw
Some Corrections have Been Included by
CAJAD
Last checking has been done.
The Energy Degradation was Calculated According to
W.A.Aron Et Al.,Aecu-663(1949).
Since the Faraday Cup Measured Only the Current Passing
The Last Foil of the Stack, a Further Determination of
The Current was done Using an Ionisation Chamber in
Front of the Stack. The Same Absorbers As Used in the
Experiment were in Turn Inserted Between the Chamber
And the Fc, and the Fraction of the Current Passing the
Respective Foils was Determined. Thus the Flux Measured
For the Individual Foils was Assumed to be of an
Accuracy Comparable to That of the Directly Measured
Incident Beam.
As an Additional Check of the Beam Monitoring Technique
The Cross Section For 340 MeV Protons For the Reaction
C-12(P,PN)C-11 was Determined by Bombarding a Plastic
Scintillator of 0.75 Inch Thickness in an Uniform
Proton Flux. Photographic Emulsions were Placed on Each
Side of the Scintillator and Proton Tracks were Counted
To Determine the Particle Flux. C-11 was Counted by
Placing the Scintillator in Contact with a
Photomultiplier Tube. The Counting Efficiency was
Determined by the Beta-Gamma Coincidence Technique
Stack Consisting of Polystyrene Foils, Thickness
Varying from 1 to 15 Mils, Carbon Energy Degrader and
Guard Foils. The Latter were Placed Between Target
Foils and Degraders.
.4Pi-Beta Counter
Calibrated Against a Similar Counter of the National
Bureau of Standards and Against a Beta-Gamma
Coincidence Counter.
Cross Section Obtained from a Foil Bombarded in
`Poor Geometry`. For Details See Under `Comment`.
Cross Section Obtained from Irradiation of 0.75
Inch Plastic Scintillator. This Measurement was
Performed to Check the Beam Monitoring Technique (SEE
UNDER `METHOD`).

Point from the 4Pi-Counter Data.

Since the Faraday Cup Measured Only the Current Passing

Respective Foils was Determined. Thus the Flux Measured
For the Individual Foils was Assumed to be of an
Accuracy Comparable to That of the Directly Measured

As an Additional Check of the Beam Monitoring Technique
The Cross Section For 340 MeV Protons For the Reaction
C-12(P,PN)C-11 was Determined by Bombarding a Plastic
Scintillator of 0.75 Inch Thickness in an Uniform
Proton Flux. Photographic Emulsions were Placed on Each
Side of the Scintillator and Proton Tracks were Counted

The Energy Degradation was Calculated According to
W.A.Aron Et Al.,Aecu-663(1949).
The Incident Particle Beam was Measured by an
Ionization Chamber and the Current Through Each Foil
Was Determined from Charge-Attenuation Curves Measured
With a Faraday Cup.
Stack Consisting of Polystyrene Foils, Thickness
Varying from 1 to 15 Mils, Carbon Energy Degrader and
Guard Foils. The Latter were Placed Between Target
Foils and Degraders.
Graphite Foils 1/8 and 1/16 Inch Thick were Placed
Between Guard Foils and Inserted at Various Depths
In Uranium Absorbers. Near the End of the Range the
Carbon Foils were Inserted Consecutively.
.4Pi-Beta Counter
Calibrated Against a Similar Counter of the National
Bureau of Standards and Against a Beta-Gamma
Coincidence Counter.
No Activity Other Than C-11 was Observed.
Cross Section Obtained from a Bombardment in
`Poor Geometry`. For Details See Under `Comment`.
The Value is Corrected by the Empirically
Determined Factor of 1/1.04 For 0.5 Inch Carbon
Absorbers and 1/1.08 For Greater Thicknesses.
By Kachapag

x4freetext: The Data were Normalized on the Basis of the
C-12(D,2N+P) Data (SEE SUBENTRY B0101003), Since Both
Curves were Measured Under the Same Experimental
Conditions. No Further Details are Given.
The Energy Degradation was Calculated According to
W.A.Aron Et Al.,Aecu-663(1949).
The Incident Particle Beam was Measured by an
Ionization Chamber and the Current Through Each Foil
Was Determined from Charge Attenuation Curves Measured
With a Faraday Cup.
Graphite Foils 1/8 and 1/16 Inch Thick were Placed
Between Guard Foils and Inserted at Various Depths
In Uranium Absorbers. Near the End of the Range the
Carbon Foils were Inserted Consecutively.
No Activity Other Than C-11 was Observed.
Large Unsymmetrical Errors were Adopted Due
To  a Possibly Incorrect Correction (SEE UNDER `FLAG`).
The Shape of the Excitation Function May be Incorrect.
. See Above.
. Any Information is Absent.
Cross Section Obtained from a Bombardment in
`Poor Geometry`. A Correction Factor of 1/1.08 was
Applied For Energies Less Than the Maximum. This
Correction, However, was Felt to be Incorrect For He-3
Particles, Since Those Secondaries, Which have
Undergone a Stripping Reaction in the Absorber, have
Ranges Greater Than the Residual Range of the He-3.
By Kachapag
